AN  - 852898086; 201103336
AB  - This paper1 presents two Western narratives of the Ilinden uprising (1903) in late Ottoman Macedonia, arguing that our present understanding of the uprising is a representation based on a political ideology, distorting our picture of the event and social dynamics in the late Ottoman Balkans. A comparative review of three British newspapers on their coverage of the period prior to, during, and in the aftermath of the Ilinden uprising shows not only that there are substantial differences within and between the Western discussions of the Balkans, but also that Western history writing is no less subjective or politically neutral than non-Western history writing. Adapted from the source document.
